.10746,0.09344,0.083091,0.067672,0.0582,0.050149],"unified_progress":[0.032448,0.073376,0.096213,0.1102,0.1173,0.10969,0.10431,0.094739,0.093448,0.070251,0.05462,0.043405]},{"section":8,"text":"The sternocleidomastoid is a large muscle in the neck, and a swelling at its upper border could indicate an abscess or a lymph node issue.","dimension":9,"group":1,"is_degenerate":false,"model_progress":[0.031613,0.071139,0.092162,0.10921,0.11326,0.11036,0.1088,0.096315,0.085804,0.06993,0.059674,0.051732],"unified_progress":[0.031664,0.071295,0.09446,0.11011,0.11697,0.10936,0.10647,0.095168,0.094816,0.071191,0.05403,0.044462]},{"section":9,"text":"Putting this together, after a tooth extraction, especially if there were complications like infection, bacteria can spread.","dimension":6,"group":8,"is_degenerate":false,"model_progress":[0.046651,0.072029,0.081962,0.088526,0.094487,0.09632,0.097076,0.095356,0.091694,0.089013,0.078361,0.068525],"unified_progress":[0.043038,0.069711,0.08146,0.090683,0.095492,0.10043,0.098596,0.09713,0.092984,0.089807,0.076922,0.063742]},{"section":10,"text":"Dental infections can lead to abscesses, and if they spread, they might form a peritonsillar abscess.","dimension":9,"group":1,"is_degenerate":false,"model_progress":[0.040682,0.058679,0.074093,0.084353,0.094342,0.098724,0.10451,0.10392,0.10011,0.091523,0.080955,0.068111],"unified_progress":[0.038184,0.062516,0.080461,0.091233,0.09811,0.10299,0.10112,0.099897,0.098565,0.090807,0.076416,0.059706]},{"section":11,"text":"Peritonsillar abscesses are collections of pus near the tonsils and can cause trismus because the pressure from the abscess makes it hard to open the mouth.","dimension":9,"group":1,"is_degenerate":false,"model_progress":[0.034911,0.061029,0.078777,0.091732,0.09988,0.10243,0.10685,0.10203,0.096559,0.08465,0.075618,0.065535],"unified_progress":[0.034058,0.067091,0.087331,0.099846,0.10693,0.10616,0.10288,0.097101,0.098744,0.080757,0.066216,0.052879]},{"section":12,"text":"The tonsils being pushed medially would make sense as the abscess pushes them to the side.","dimension":9,"group":1,"is_degenerate":false,"model_progress":[0.033163,0.05837,0.077631,0.091959,0.10065,0.10336,0.10661,0.1019,0.097428,0.086682,0.076702,0.065552],"unified_progress":[0.032146,0.064228,0.084371,0.097499,0.10584,0.10468,0.10343,0.098519,0.098934,0.084892,0.069275,0.056189]},{"section":13,"text":"Another possibility is Ludwig's angina, which is a type of cellulitis in the floor of the mouth, but that usually causes more swelling in the floor of the mouth and doesn't specifically mention the sternocleidomastoid area.","dimension":9,"group":1,"is_degenerate":false,"model_progress":[0.03121,0.058921,0.076155,0.089019,0.09764,0.1009,0.10583,0.10301,0.098511,0.089449,0.079776,0.069572],"unified_progress":[0.031266,0.063016,0.082739,0.09625,0.10333,0.10705,0.10342,0.09859,0.098259,0.084999,0.071661,0.05941]},{"section":14,"text":"Also, Ludwig's angina is more associated with bilateral neck swelling and airway compromise, which isn't mentioned here.","dimension":12,"group":4,"is_degenerate":false,"model_progress":[0.030461,0.053419,0.07047,0.081564,0.09264,0.098361,0.10466,0.10611,0.10471,0.097865,0.087391,0.072346],"unified_progress":[0.03607,0.06201,0.07723,0.087749,0.095497,0.10266,0.10087,0.10091,0.098594,0.094707,0.080188,0.063515]},{"section":15,"text":"Then there's the possibility of a retropharyngeal abscess, but that's usually deeper and might not present with a specific swelling at the sternocleidomastoid.","dimension":9,"group":1,"is_degenerate":false,"model_progress":[0.028711,0.05465,0.070561,0.082152,0.091947,0.097496,0.10383,0.10427,0.1033,0.097187,0.088863,0.077036],"unified_progress":[0.032657,0.063217,0.079913,0.091302,0.098014,0.10004,0.099962,0.098835,0.10018,0.090992,0.079275,0.065617]},{"section":16,"text":"So, considering the history of tooth extraction, fever, trismus, and the physical findings, peritonsillar abscess seems the most likely diagnosis.",